Nasa spokesman.<br>
<br>
Remember back to when you were a lot younger, more impressionable and yes naive. If you are about my age then you probably watched Dr Who, the original Star Trek and the first Star Wars movies. Now sequels apparently. Those and a host of other classic science fiction shows essentially made for kids. I recall every kid wanting his own spaceship.<br>
<br>
Getting from A to B.<br>
<br>
Public transport comes in two types. Smaller personal transports such as cars and bikes are by far the most popular. Larger mass transport systems like planes, trains, ships and buses are essential in this busy world aswell though. Not just for moving people but goods aswell. Now why are rockets so expensive? Can they be made cheaper and do any alternatives exist? Most of us take exhorbitant launch costs for granted. We are used to paying out heavy sums for car repairs and keep watching petrol pump prices soar. It isn't difficult to understand how heavier vehicles will consume vastly more fuel and require greater maintenance. Equating one transportation system with more familiar ones is only natural but spaceflight is markedly different to other means of getting aropund. We aren't moving from one point on the Earths surface to another. The destination is off planet entirely.<br>
Cars eventually replaced horse drawn carriages not because of superior performance as is popularly believed, but because they proved cheaper. Owning a team of horses was expensive. In 1904 one man calculated that over 5 years his car had cost him $1400, while the total expense of keeping a pair of horses and a carriage had been $2200. Much of the driving force behind innovative car development has come from motor racing. Tyres, lights, fuels, brakes, suspension, chassis and engine parts were given a gruelling test in early events such as the Dunlop trial between Sydney and Melbourne in the same year. Airplanes, like the car, were initially a novelty and only became practical after 1930's racing events and commercialisation took it to new levels. Now it outcompetes all other means of transporatation in terms of speed and distance.<br>
So why hasn't space travel become an everyday method of transportation. We saw competition between rival superpowers put men on the moon. Big buisness invests millions into putting up commercial satellites. The competition is clearly there and so is the commercial motivation. Whats missing?<br>
<br>
Power.<br>
<br>
The first cars were not an immediate success. The era of steam driven locomotion was certainly eventful but never resulted in an affordable automobile or working plane. It did however give rise to trains which then opened up the American frontier. A more compact energy source was required to build a practical horseless carriage. Oil based products such as petrol and diesel proved to be that fuel. They were far better than coal or wood but for space travel we had to devise even more compact chemical fuels and even they are sorely inadequate. A typical trip to the edge of space requires an inordinate amount of chemical fuel. Something like 85 - 90% of total mass. Reaching the moon required a 5 stage rocket. <br>
